content.description: SDS at lowest point (corner closest to Jenga) with high heel hook. Traverse left and up to a tricky mantle top-out.    A good warmup for the harder routes in the area.
content.location: Overhanging lip about 5 feet left of Jenga

content.description:
At the Jenga Boulder and looking for something to do?  You are probably standing next to this.

Start sitting in the little roof, right hand on a pinch, left on a low fin.  A heal toe cam could be useful.  Gain the lip and probably move left a little to finish.
content.location: The little roof next to the Jenga Boulder.

content.description: Left hand on a down pulling sloper down and right of the Jenga start hold and right hand below the roof on a pockety sidepull.  Do a few extra fun moves into Jenga.
Start down left on obvious jug, and work your way out right to corner and up to top. The Double heel hook works great to hold yourself on.
content.location: I found it by hiking up through the 500ft. boulder field to the top where it meets the slanted boulder field.  Jenga sits right at the top just past the slab.    See here for alternate beta:wisconsinbouldering.blogspo…

content.description: Start on Jenga and move into the stand start of Hungry Hippos.  It turned out to be a surprisingly natural line with really cool movement.
Start with right hand on good edge and left hand on the upper sloper of Jenga.  Set feet and work your way up and right to gain good jug.
content.protection: Pads and spotters.  Like much of the talus climbing, injury potential is high without enough pads.
content.location: Just to the right of Jenga.

content.description: Start left hand on good edge from Jenga on the arete, jump to decent right hand crimp, and go up to topout.
content.protection: Pads.  It could be really bad to ping off the swinging toehook move or the final dyno.  There is a drop off into the talus if you do miss the landing.  Be careful!
content.location: Jenga boulder, stand start (jump) on face facing the Lake.

content.description:
Awesome 15 foot roof offwith in a cave. 

  Start by laying on your back and throwing your feet into the crack at the lowest point in the roof, about 15 feet into the cave. Climb the wide crack going through a couple of rocks that are stuck in the crack (they are on). When you reach the end of the crack, climb the cruxy roof to gain the jugs at the point. Continue on good holds to the top. 

  You may need to take a couple of minutes to clean out roots and debris that like to gather in the crack.
content.protection: 4 pads for full coverage. I recommend a thin pad at the end to help prevent dabbing. Headlamps/lanterns recommended but not needed.
content.location: A cave 5 feet from the top out of Jenga.

content.description: Start as for Jenga and climbing into Falling to Pieces and finish as for that problem.  A tough and wild linkup that is clearly very forced.

Start Left hand on a downpulling sloper down and right from the Jenga start hold and right hand down and right under the roof on a pockety sidepull.  Compress your way up and finish on Hungry Hippos.  A really fun hard problem.
